04621nam a22005295i 9780774856683DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19901990xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748566837 a10.59962/97807748566832doi  a(DE-B1597)662307  a(OCoLC)1227639569  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aLE3.B82bS74 1990eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a378.711/331 aStewart, Lee, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIt's Up to You :bWomen at UBC in the Early Years /cLee Stewart. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[1990] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (204 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tA University to Serve the Needs of All the People -- tIn the Back Door: Nursing at UBC -- tThe Proper and Logical Study for Womankind: Home Economics at UBC -- tA Position of Adequate Authority: A Dean’s Office for Women -- tMore Than a Roof and a Bed: Rooms of Their Own -- tBoys’ Rules: The Masculine Institution and the Feminine Image -- tGirls’ Rules: Accommodating Women to the Female Reality -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLee Stewart argues in this book that the notion of university education as a cultural entitlement, inherent in the literal translation of the University of British Columbia's motto Tuum Est as 'It is yours,' has always been more applicable to male than to female students. Conversely, the popular interpretation of Tuum Est, 'It's up to you,' has held greater significance for women. Stewart examines the demands, accomplishments, and limitations of women advocates and educators against the background of the social and cultural conditions which enveloped them. \ The book profiles the experience of women at UBC from the founding of the university early inthis century until after the Second World War. Stewart argues that campaigns to open the university, to start nursing and home economic programs, to establish the office of dean of women, and to build women's residences each involved the persistent efforts of women reformers, and each eventually succeeded. At the same time, pragmatism, politics, and expedience, far more than a passion for feminism within the university or in the province, accounted for the form that these programs and institutions took. Stewart also describes the experience of female students and the strategies they devised to participate fully in the academic, cultural, and political life of the university. Young women had to juggle the contradictory expectations of the academic and social communities. In describing this process the author consciously links women's experience to the history of the university itself. Stewart makes an important contribution to our understanding of higher education and to the history of a major Canadian university. She also expands our sensitivity to women's changing role in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311141940440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485668340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774856683423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774856683/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  